WAYMO.name: Waymo
WAYMO.tagline: The world's most experienced driver — autonomous driving technology subsidiary of Alphabet Inc.
WAYMO.overview: Waymo LLC is an autonomous driving technology company and subsidiary of Alphabet Inc. Originally started as Google's Self-Driving Car Project in 2009, Waymo became a standalone company in 2016. The company operates Waymo One, the world's first commercial autonomous ride-hailing service, across 5 US cities: Phoenix, San Francisco, Los Angeles, Austin, and Atlanta. As of April 2025, Waymo provides 250,000+ paid rides per week (over 1 million miles monthly) with a fleet of 2,500 robotaxis. In November 2025, Waymo became the first US company to offer fully autonomous freeway rides at up to 65 mph. In October 2024, Waymo raised $5.6 billion at a $45 billion valuation, with backing from Alphabet, Andreessen Horowitz, Fidelity, Tiger Global, and Silver Lake. Expansion to Miami, San Diego, Washington D.C., Tokyo, and London planned for 2026.

WEBFLOW.name: Webflow
WEBFLOW.tagline: Empowering designers and developers to build professional websites visually without writing code
WEBFLOW.overview: Webflow is a no-code website builder that enables designers and developers to create professional websites visually. Founded in 2013 by Vlad Magdalin, the company raised $335M at $4B valuation in March 2022. Revenue reached $213M in 2024, up from $128M in 2023. Webflow powers millions of websites and has become a leader in the no-code movement. The company has stated they have no plans for an IPO, focusing instead on long-term product development. Analysts project potential $7-10B valuation if growth continues.

WEALTHSIMPLE.name: Wealthsimple
WEALTHSIMPLE.tagline: Making financial independence achievable for everyone through accessible investing and savings tools
WEALTHSIMPLE.overview: Wealthsimple is Canada's largest independent investment management firm, founded in 2014 by Michael Katchen. The company offers investing, trading, crypto, tax filing, and savings products. In October 2025, Wealthsimple raised CAD $750M at $10B valuation—doubling from a year prior. The company reached CAD $100B in assets under administration (up from $50B in 2024) and serves 3M Canadians. Wealthsimple was profitable in 2024 and continues to be in 2025, with plans to launch its first credit card and expand into more financial services.

WAYVE.name: Wayve
WAYVE.tagline: Pioneering Embodied AI for autonomous driving with end-to-end deep learning technology
WAYVE.overview: Wayve is a British autonomous driving technology company founded in 2017 by Alex Kendall and Amar Shah, two machine learning PhD students from the University of Cambridge. The company pioneers Embodied AI for self-driving vehicles, using end-to-end deep learning that enables vehicles to learn from experience rather than relying on detailed maps or hand-coded rules. Unlike traditional autonomous vehicle systems that depend on expensive LiDAR sensors and high-definition maps, Wayve's approach uses primarily camera data and AI that can adapt to new environments without geofenced limits. The company was the first to deploy end-to-end deep learning autonomous vehicles on public roads. Headquartered in London with offices in California, Vancouver, Germany, and Japan, Wayve has raised over $1.3 billion from investors including SoftBank, Microsoft, Nvidia, and Uber. The company is currently in talks to raise an additional $2 billion at an $8 billion valuation. Wayve's vision is to create a "general purpose" driving AI that can power all levels of automation in any vehicle, anywhere in the world.

WHATNOT.name: Whatnot
WHATNOT.tagline: The largest livestream shopping platform connecting buyers and sellers in real-time across collectibles, fashion, sneakers, and 250+ categories
WHATNOT.overview: Whatnot is the largest livestream shopping platform in the United States, United Kingdom, and Europe, founded in 2019 by Grant LaFontaine and Logan Head. The platform revolutionizes e-commerce by combining live video auctions, community engagement, and entertainment to create an interactive shopping experience. Whatnot connects millions of buyers and sellers in real-time across over 250 categories, including collectibles like trading cards, comic books, sports memorabilia, Funko Pops, as well as fashion, sneakers, beauty products, electronics, plants, and vintage items. As of October 2025, Whatnot has achieved a valuation of $11.5 billion following a $225 million Series F funding round, more than doubling its valuation since January 2025. The platform hosts over 175,000 hours of livestreams weekly and has facilitated over $6 billion in gross merchandise value in 2025 alone, more than twice its total for all of 2024.

highlights.text: Whatnot continues to grow and expand
